Using count() to aggregate data
count() is a shortcut for grouping and summarizing the data.
For example, if we want to get the total number of complete rows for each state, then ::: {.cell layout-align=‚Äúcenter‚Äù}
cases_count &lt;- cases_df |&gt;
  drop_na() |&gt; # Removes rows where any value is missing (from tidyr)
  group_by(geo_value) |&gt;
  summarize(count = n())
:::  is equivalent to

cases_count &lt;- cases_df |&gt;
  drop_na() |&gt;
  count(geo_value)

